@@gThe Eccentric Woodland@@N

  Midgaard's @@ysouthern pressure-valve frontier@@N: a nearby forest that
never fully accepted city law, yet never fully escaped city influence.
It orbits Midgaard without belonging to it. Travelers leaving the
Southern Wild Gate expect a conventional transition -- city wall,
patrol road, outer farmland, then untamed canopy. Instead, the
Woodland presents inconsistent geography and mood.

  Clearings feel pastoral for an hour and predatory by dusk. Old game
paths move or close. Isolated halls maintained by groups with their
own ritual authority dot the interior. Signs of staged violence may
be ambush, theater, or warning depending on who interprets them.

  Before Midgaard paved its southern districts, the land beyond the
ninth milestone was navigated by @@dbell walkers@@N -- shepherd-priests
who rang a single bell at dusk to guide the lost. When the city
formalized under the First Stone Accord, southern roads were secured
only to the point where caravans could stage safely overnight. The
interior was never comprehensively chartered.

  During the Lantern Reforms, survey clerks tried to standardize the
area. They failed. Patrol reports noted path drift, contradictory
witness accounts, and landmarks that could not be relocated. The
name @@g"Eccentric Woodland"@@N entered civic usage as a registry
convenience admitting irregular behavior while still assigning it
a ledger category.

  Four kinds of authority contest the interior. @@ePath Wardens@@N sell
navigation and protection as informal guides and scouts. @@dRitual
Houses@@N are enclosed groups using oath language and symbolic spaces
to legitimate rank through dueling rooms, binding circles, and
ceremony. @@rPredator Bands@@N mimic ritual forms to induce fear and
compliance among travelers. @@eSurvivor Clusters@@N occupy burrows,
caves, and clearings as temporary refuge and barter points.

  None of these fully controls the Woodland. Power is local, contingent,
and often theatrical. Midgaard's current position is @@ymanaged denial@@N:
the city acknowledges the hazard, preserves pass checks and route
advisories to reduce liability, and avoids full intervention because
sustained control would require forces diverted from higher-priority
corridors.

  The Woodland demonstrates what happens when Midgaard's core doctrine
-- order as infrastructure -- is applied only at the boundary. First
Stone logic breaks where roads no longer return to watched squares.
Lantern logic breaks where posted notices cannot stabilize terrain
that resists repeatable pathing. The Woodland is governance at its
thinnest, within walking distance of the southern gates.
